DISCLAIMER
Some investigations around performance.
This code is made available to anyone and is not related to GATTACA SOFTWARE.

Usage

We provide a helper script run_udp_test.sh that runs the UDP receiver + sender locally and aggregates performance statistics (pps, Mb/s).

Build
CMake (macOS)

Build the receiver in release mode:

cmake -B cmake-build-release -DCMAKE_BUILD_TYPE=Release
cmake --build cmake-build-release
Makefile (Linux / no CMake)

If you don’t have CMake, you can use the Makefile to build the receiver binary.




**********************************************************
************
*** Goal ***
************
Investigate “kernel bypass” — the thing you keep hearing about in HFT — and understand what it really buys (PPS, latency, jitter), starting from a clean UDP baseline.

Work on 31/03/2026

1) First reality check: remote Mac → VPS

I started by sending UDP from my Mac to a Debian VPS.
I quickly hit a hard ceiling: the VPS path looked bandwidth-limited / shaped around ~5–6 Mb/s.
Conclusion: as long as I’m testing over the public Internet to that VPS, I’m mostly measuring network shaping, not kernel/socket limits. So that’s not the right setup to learn “kernel bypass”.

2) Move the test to localhost to remove the network bottleneck

I switched to running sender/receiver on the same machine so I could actually stress the OS/kernel path.
That immediately exposed a configuration trap: I was sending UDP_PAYLOAD_SIZE=512 but receiving with UDP_BUFFER_SIZE=8.
Result: the receiver was silently truncating each datagram, so server Mb/s looked completely wrong (bytes/packet ≈ 8). PPS could look “ok” while throughput was nonsense.
Fix: enforce the only sane rule — recv buffer must be ≥ payload — and fail fast if not.

3) Tooling cleanup (so benchmarks aren’t polluted by config drift)

I removed .env logic from the Python sender because it created hidden state and mismatches (CLI vs env vs scripts).
I made the C++ receiver strict: no defaults, explicit flags, and a hard guard buffer >= payload.
I made the bash runner “production-ish”: fail fast, and detect receiver startup failure properly (background process failures don’t stop a script by themselves).

4) Scale test: where is the real bottleneck?

At 20k PPS localhost, receiver tracks the sender closely (small drop rate, normal for UDP + OS scheduling).
When I asked for 500k PPS, I did not get 500k PPS: the Python sender topped out around ~135k PPS.
The receiver tracked that rate closely, so the bottleneck at that point was clearly the Python generator, not the receiver/kernel.
Where I’m at now (facts)
Remote tests to the VPS are dominated by bandwidth shaping → not useful for kernel bypass investigation.
Localhost tests are valid now (config fixed, tools strict).
Python is not a credible sender for high PPS; it caps far below the range where “kernel bypass” becomes relevant.
What I’ll do tomorrow
Write a C/C++ UDP sender (CLI-only, deterministic) to replace Python.
Goal: actually push into 500k PPS, 1M PPS territory without the interpreter choking first.
Run a controlled PPS sweep locally:
200k → 500k → 1M+ PPS
Measure client vs server PPS to quantify drops and find the real ceiling.
If drops show up early:
Increase/verify socket receive buffer (SO_RCVBUF, and print actual value with getsockopt).
Reduce runtime logging noise (final stats only) to avoid jitter artifacts.

Once the pure kernel/socket path is clearly characterized, then it makes sense to compare against a true kernel-bypass path (DPDK/AF_XDP/etc.) and see what changes in PPS/latency/jitter.